passages.text: **Equity Research** August 29, 2025
F2Q Not a Singularity Eve, Achievable Guide Indicates Future Remains Bright

F2Q 24% yoy ARR growth beat cons by $16M driven by better execution. FY26 rev guide was only raised by $2M at midpoint which raised some questions but we view it as prudent (welcome given historical volatility). Improved execution,a broadening prod portfolio coupled with a newly unveiled Flex offering should help penetrate the enterprise and sustain growth. Shares AH remain attractive at just 5.4x CY26 rev. Remain buy, PT $25

**Strong** **F2Q** **NNARR.** S reported ARR of $1,001M, which beat cons by approx. $16M. F2Q incremental ARR (not accounting for churn) showed positive sequential growth to ~$53M (vs $28M in 1Q). If we account for churn, we calculate that new business grew 25% yoy in F2Q vs down 7% in F1Q on a flat comp making the execution notable. While some of this was from slipped F1Q deals (not quantified), the majority of this strength was new logo and cross-sell traction. While it is likely too early to account for success from the new Flex program in the F2Q beat, it is fair to assume that NNARR will follow an improved shape & likely grow in 2H given the raised FY26 revenue guide.

**F3Q** **&** **FY26** **NNARR** **Assumptions.** Given the outsized strength in F2Q, we model $1.052B of ARR in F3Q (22% yoy, flat yoy new business accounting for churn). We believe this flat new business yoy assumption is reasonable relative to F2Q's +25% yoy growth given the comp is 13 pts tougher. We model 5% yoy growth in new business in F4Q which ultimately drives FY26 ARR growth to 21% yoy (1 pt higher than cons' pre-print expectations).

**F2Q** **Revenue** **Only** **In-line** **With** **Cons** **Despite** **Huge** **ARR** **Beat.** S reported F2Q rev of $242M (22% yoy) in line with consensus despite ARR beating cons by $16M. Management pointed out a very back-end loaded quarter and some pro services headwinds as the reason for no revenue upside.While this is logical, we will continue to monitor given other endpoint vendors are experiencing revenue headwinds related to partner incentives.

**Modestly** **Raised** **Guide** **for** **FY26** **Rev.** While S beat F2Q cons ARR by $16M, it only raised FY26 rev by $2M at the midpoint, if we flow through the $16M of ARR upside, full year rev guidance should have been raised by $2M (assumes ratable rev recog. given 2 Q's remaining in the fiscal year). Mgmt noted some potential services headwinds but ultimately we view FY26 rev guide as incrementally prudent which is a welcome change given historical execution volatility. We believe this is a great first step in resetting investor expectations to more manageable top-line targets.

SentinelOne provides a state- of- the- art, AI- powered, next- gen endpoint platform that has sizable opportunity before it to help companies respond to endpoint and other threats in a more automated capacity. SentinelOne's platform is in the right place and right time, given security has taken on greater importance with WFH creating a more distributed network and with the increasing number of large- scale breaches.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

- Emerges as one of the leaders in the market for endpoint security but also continues to add modules, which expands the addressable market and maintains hypergrowth.- Customers continue to purchase multiple solutions, and the net retention rate stays consistently at or above \(110\% .\)- SentinelOne is consistently sustainably free-cash-flow-positive- \(\) 25\(PT is DCF - derived and implies\) 7.2x EV/ \(CY26E revenue.\)

- Emerges as the industry standard vs CRWD for endpoint security but also continues to add modules, which expands the addressable market and maintains hypergrowth.- Progress in operating leverage better than expected.- Customers purchase more solutions than expected and the net retention rate stays consistently above \(110\% .\)- \(\) 35\(PT is DCF derived and implies\) 10x EV/ \(CY26E revenue.\)

- Revenue growth decelerates faster than expected due to increased competition in the endpoint market.- The company has to continue paying commissions on renewals, which decreases future potential operating leverage.- Needs to make continued investments to remain relevant in the marketplace, further delaying cash flow consistency.- \(\) 15\(PT is DCF derived and implies\) 4x EV/CY26E revenue.

Top Material Issues: (1) Data, Security. Cybersecurity companies play a crucial role both in taking responsibility for maintaining data security and in ensuring customers have access to the products and services required to achieve data security. We expect to see continued focus on data security with a threat landscape that continues to grow. (2) Employee, Engagement, Diversity & Inclusion. We see company culture as important, and/or market that continues to be defined by a skill shortage. Additionally, given the known underrepresentation of women and minority groups in the software industry today, a focus on building a diverse workforce is cardinal.
Company Targets: No quantifiable targets have been given.

Q's to Mgmt: (1) When can we expect more definitive targets on how you aim to reduce your impact on the environment? (2) How has the focus on data security by your customers changed over the past 24 months? (3) What are some of the definitive actions you are taking to diversify your workforce, do you have any DEI initiatives?

- Successful expansion internationally results in outsized growth for years, leading to improvement in operating leverage.- Acceleration of new customer growth and maintaining strong gross retention rates.- Continued successful execution of company's land and expand strategy leads to continued strength net revenue retention and improved operating leverage.
Software Sector ESG Integration Refresh

This. We view S as a clear top 2 vendor in Endpoint, with strong future growth tailwinds including 1) the Lenovo partnership, 2) a potentially improving macro relative to April (management noted no change) 3) Flex offerings allowing it to move market and displace incumbent vendors in various categories. etc. 5.4x AH CY26 rev for a unique asset growing \(20\% +\) remains very compelling in our view. Our \(\) 25\(PT implies 7.2x CY26 rev.

Prompt Security Acquisition Specifics. Earlier this month, S announced an agreement to acquire Prompt Security, a Gen AI security company. Management disclosed the purchase price for the transaction is \(\sim\) 180M; the deal is expected to close in FQ3. From a financial perspective, management expects insignificant ARR/revenue contribution for FY26 and an 80bps drag on FY operating margin. While it will take time for AI security products to translate to meaningful revenue contribution, we view Prompt as a logical addition to S' Singularity platform.

Mgmt Still Cautious With Macro. Comments on macro leaned prudent with management addressing the environment as dynamic and evolving. While management didn't offer any explicit dismissal of comments it made in 1Q about macro uncertainty/volatility and Fed uncertainties, it referenced positive demand signals and a healthy pipeline. Revenue guidance continues to factor in the potential for timing variability among larger deals. We acknowledge this could create room for a larger beat in F3Q/4Q, provided that execution and the macro backdrop remains consistent.

Positive on Purple AI. Consistent with last quarter, Purple AI bookings growth exceeded triple- digits. Additionally, it delivered record attach rates of \(>30\%\) of all subscriptions sold in the quarter. It has been one year since Purple AI became generally available, and we continue to be impressed with performance.

Op Margin Trajectory. F2Q non- GAAP op margin came in strong at \(2.2\%\) versus consensus of \(0.1\%\) and reflected a \(\sim 500\) bps increase yoy. For FY26, non- GAAP op margin guidance of \(3.0\%\) was slightly below consensus of \(3.3\%\) . However, excluding the 80bps headwind from the Prompt AI acquisition, FY guidance would have beat modestly by 50bps. F3Q non- GAAP op margin was guided to \(4\%\) , which represents a 900 bps expansion yoy. We continue to believe that significant operating leverage can be unlocked over the next 12- 24 months as S executes at scale. While S still materially lags where CRWD was at similar scale, we view this as opportunity on margin expansion.

Cash Flow to Uplift in 2H. Free cash flow narrowly disappointed in F2Q, coming in at a loss of \(\) 7.1M\(versus a consensus gain of\) \ \(2.1M\) (likely due to a very back- end weighted Q). On a TTM basis, FCF was positive at a \(2\%\) margin. Management expects a stronger F2H26 with respect to cash flow. We model FCF margins at \(\sim 5.3\%\) for FY26, approximately 200bps north of non- GAAP operating margin (in- line with management commentary).

SentinelOne Flex. S announced the launch of SentinelOne Flex, its modular licensing model for the Singularity platform. We view this as a step in the right direction as customers continue to shift preferences toward more dynamic offerings. Flex is expected to have positive impacts on deal size, duration, and adoption while also improving the sales process. Management pointed to its largest deal in the quarter, an 8- figure total deal value Flex signing with a multinational conglomerate. We expect this new model to disproportionately benefit non endpoint (AI, cloud, data) bookings (currently \(\sim 50\%\) of total bookings) as they see meaningful deployment pickup.

SentinelOne (S) was founded in 2013 and build an Al- powered extended detection and response, or XDR, platform to make cybersecurity defense truly autonomous, from the endpoint and beyond. The Singularity Platform instantly defends against cyberattacks - performing at a faster speed, greater scale, and higher accuracy than possible from any single human. SentinelOne has its headquarters in Mountain View, California and also has offices in Israel, Japan, United Arab Emirates, and the Netherlands.

Our \(\) 25\$ price target is based on a DCF and implies \(7x EV / CY26E revenue. Upside risks include emergence as the industry standard vs. CRWD and successful international expansion. Downside risks include rapid deceleration of revenue growth due to increased competition.
Our \(\) 500\$ price target equates to 21x EV/CY26E rev and is one of the most expensive in our coverage universe. Risks include competition, slower market growth, and delayed profitability.
